// @log true
// @log true
// A directly-used (un-bound) string literal is ALWAYS a `string` — a WasmGC
// i32-array of char codes — of ANY length, including 1. So `"a".length` /
// `"\n".length` resolve `.length` (array.len) without first binding to a `let`,
// and a one-char string literal is NOT confused with a char literal `'a'` (an
// i32). Indexing a literal yields an i32 char code; a char literal stays an i32.
print("a".length == 1)     // a length-1 string literal is a string, not a char
print("\n".length == 1)    // an escaped one-char string literal is still a string
print("abc".length == 3)   // multi-char string literal
print("ab"[0] == 'a')      // indexing a string literal yields an i32 char code
print('a' == 97)           // a char literal is an i32 code point (unchanged)
